column1: :has_definition ""A venous insufficiency that is characterized by aching pain, heaviness, swelling, cramps, itching, or tingling in the affected limb and is a chronic complication of deep venous thrombosis.""

,Post thrombotic syndrome is a type of venous insufficiency characterized by aching pain, heaviness, swelling, cramps, itching, or tingling in the affected limb and is a chronic complication of deep venous thrombosis. It has exact synonyms including Postphlebetic syndrome with inflammation, Postphlebetic syndrome with ulcer, Postphlebetic syndrome with ulcer and inflammation, postphlebitic syndrome, and venous stress disorder.",7,True

:has_definition ""A viral infectious disease that results in inflammation located in brain, has_material_basis_in West Nile virus, which is transmitted_by Culex, Aedes, or Anopheles species of mosquitoes. The infection has_symptom high fever, has_symptom headache, has_symptom neck stiffness, has_symptom stupor, has_symptom disorientation, has_symptom coma, has_symptom tremors, has_symptom convulsions, has_symptom muscle weakness, has_symptom vision loss, has_symptom numbness, and has_symptom paralysis.""

,West Nile encephalitis is a type of viral infectious disease that also falls under the category of brain disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in the West Nile virus and is transmitted by mosquitoes belonging to the Aedes, Anopheles, or Culex genera. This disease manifests with symptoms such as confusion, disorientation, paralysis, muscle weakness, tremor, stiff neck, stupor, paresthesia, headache, convulsion, coma, and high fever. Specifically, West Nile encephalitis is a condition that results in inflammation located in the brain, which is caused by the West Nile virus. This virus is transmitted by species of Culex, Aedes, or Anopheles mosquitoes. The infection leads to symptoms including high fever, headache, neck stiffness, stupor, disorientation, coma, tremors, convulsions, muscle weakness, vision loss, numbness, and paralysis. Moreover, the disease is also known by the exact synonyms ""West Nile Fever with encephalitis"" and ""West Nile fever encephalitis.""",20,True

:has_definition ""A viral infectious disease that results_in infection, has_material_basis_in West Nile virus, which is transmitted_by Culex and transmitted_by Aedes mosquitoes. The infection has_symptom fever, has_symptom sore throat, has_symptom headache, has_symptom body ache, has_symptom nausea, has_symptom maculopapular rash and has_symptom vomiting."" .

,West Nile fever is a type of viral infectious disease with a material basis in the West Nile virus. It is transmitted by mosquitoes of the Culex genus and possibly others like Aedes. The symptoms of West Nile fever include body ache, nausea, headache, fever, maculopapular rash, vomiting, and pharynx inflammation. The disease is defined as a viral infectious condition resulting in infection, primarily caused by the West Nile virus, transmitted through Culex and Aedes mosquitoes, and characterized by a range of symptoms including fever, sore throat, headache, body ache, nausea, maculopapular rash, and vomiting.",11,True
,Neuroaxonal dystrophy is a type of cerebral degeneration, which is a disease that affects the cerebrum.",2,True
:has_definition ""A sphingolipidosis that is characterized by the accumulation of lipids known as gangliosides."" .

,Gangliosidosis is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of sphingolipidosis, which is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a sphingolipidosis that is characterized by the accumulation of lipids known as gangliosides.",4,True
:has_definition ""A hematopoietic system disease characterized by oval or elliptical red blood cells, slight or absent hemolysis with little or no anemia
,Hereditary elliptocytosis is a type of hematopoietic system disease characterized by oval or elliptical red blood cells, slight or absent hemolysis with little or no anemia
column2: splenomegaly is often present. It is also exactly synonymous with congenital elliptocytosis and ovalocytosis.",4,True

column1: :has_definition ""A demyelinating disease that involves damage to the fatty myelin sheaths around the axons of the brain and spinal cord resulting in demyelination and scarring.""

,Multiple sclerosis is classified as a type of autoimmune disease specifically affecting the central nervous system, as well as being recognized as a demyelinating disease. It represents an intersection of conditions that are autoimmune diseases and those that are diseases located in the central nervous system. Multiple sclerosis is defined as a demyelinating disease that results in damage to the fatty myelin sheaths surrounding the axons of the brain and spinal cord, leading to demyelination and scarring. It is exactly synonymous with Generalized multiple sclerosis and Insular sclerosis. Additionally, multiple sclerosis has an exact match in the Medical Subject Headings (MESH) database with the identifier MESH:D009103.",7,True

:has_definition ""A multiple sclerosis that is characterized by relapse (attacks of symptom flare-ups) followed by remission (periods of recovery). Symptoms may vary from mild to severe, and relapses and remissions may last for days or months. More than 80 percent of people who have MS begin with relapsing-remitting cycles.""

,Relapsing-remitting multiple sclerosis (RRMS), also known as Relapsing-remitting MS, is a type of multiple sclerosis characterized by relapse (attacks of symptom flare-ups) followed by remission (periods of recovery). Symptoms can range from mild to severe, with relapses and remissions lasting for days or months. Notably, more than 80 percent of people who have multiple sclerosis start with these relapsing-remitting cycles.",4,True

:has_definition ""A brain disease that is characterized by the presence of neurological symptoms of ophthalmoplegia, ataxia, and confusion caused by biochemical lesions of the central nervous system after exhaustion of B-vitamin reserves, in particular thiamine (vitamin B1).""

It is defined as a brain disease characterized by neurological symptoms of ophthalmoplegia, ataxia, and confusion, resulting from biochemical lesions of the central nervous system after the exhaustion of B-vitamin reserves, especially thiamine (vitamin B1). This condition notably has symptoms including at least some ataxia and confusion.",6,True

,Langerhans cell histiocytosis is a type of histiocytosis and also a type of condition that at least has the phenotype of some abnormal pulmonary interstitial morphology. It is characterized by clonal proliferation of Langerhans cells. This condition is known by several exact synonyms: Histiocytosis X, Langerhan's cell histiocytosis, Langerhans cell granulomatosis, and multiple forms of Letterer-Siwe disease. These forms of Letterer-Siwe disease can involve various lymph nodes and regions, including intra-abdominal, intrapelvic, intrathoracic lymph nodes, lymph nodes of the axilla and upper limb, head, face, and neck, inguinal region and lower limb, multiple sites, as well as the spleen. Variations in the naming reflect specific involvements of lymph nodes or regions as well as slight variations in phrasing, such as ""involving"" versus ""of"" and the inclusion or exclusion of conjunctions like ""and"" or ""and/or.""",28,True

This condition is caused by indoor pollutants, including formaldehyde fumes, particulate matter, or microorganisms. The symptoms tend to disappear when affected individuals leave the building. Additionally, hepatic vascular disease is exactly synonymous with the term ""vascular disorder of liver.""",5,True
:has_definition ""A dermatitis that selectively affects the hands and feet.""

,Acrodermatitis is a type of dermatitis that has a specific definition: it is a dermatitis that selectively affects the hands and feet. Additionally, acrodermatitis has an exact match with the MESH code D000169.",3,True
:has_definition ""A skin disease characterized by itchy, erythematous, vesicular, weeping and crusting patches of skin.""

:has_definition ""A hemangioma that is characterized by the presence of capillary-sized vascular channels without prominent epithelioid endothelial cells.""

,Capillary hemangioma is a type of benign neoplasm that occurs in bones and is also recognized as a form of hemangioma. It's associated with orbital diseases and is notably derived, at least in part, from endothelial cells. Furthermore, it has a specific location within the orbital region. Capillary hemangioma is defined as a hemangioma characterized by the presence of capillary-sized vascular channels without prominent epithelioid endothelial cells. It is known by various exact synonyms, including Capillary haemangioma, Congenital vascular hamartoma, Congenital vascular naevus, Infantile hemangioma, Juvenile hemangioma, Strawberry haemangioma, Strawberry nevus, Strawberry nevus of skin, and Cellular hemangioma of Infancy.",15,True

:has_definition ""A skin disease characterized by cutaneous pigmentation, premature graying, dystrophy of the nails, leukoplakia of the oral mucosa, continuous lacrimation due to atresia of the lacrimal ducts, often thrombocytopenia, anemia, testicular atrophy in the male carriers and predisposition to cancer.""

,Dyskeratosis congenita, also known exactly as DKCD, is identified as a digenic disease, which is a subset of skin diseases. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in some form of digenic inheritance. The definition of dyskeratosis congenita outlines it as a skin disease marked by various symptoms including cutaneous pigmentation, premature graying, nail dystrophy, leukoplakia of the oral mucosa, continuous lacrimation due to atresia of the lacrimal ducts, and it often accompanies thrombocytopenia, anemia, testicular atrophy in male carriers, along with a predisposition to cancer.",5,True

:has_definition ""A vesiculobullous skin disease that is characterized by formation of blisters with only minor skin trauma, which can cause widespread wounds, dehydration, electrolyte abnormalities, and severe infection, frequently develops_from mutations in connective tissue elements, including genes encoding keratin, collagen, and laminin.""

,Epidermolysis bullosa is a type of vesiculobullous skin disease and has the exact synonym acantholysis bullosa. It is defined as a vesiculobullous skin disease characterized by the formation of blisters with only minor skin trauma, which can cause widespread wounds, dehydration, electrolyte abnormalities, and severe infection. This condition frequently develops from mutations in connective tissue elements, including genes encoding keratin, collagen, and laminin.",3,True
:has_definition ""A bullous skin disease that is characterized by fluid filled blisters."" .
,Vesiculobullous skin disease is a type of bullous skin disease, characterized by fluid-filled blisters.",2,True

,Rothmund Thomson Syndrome is a type of skin disease, also known exactly as Congenital Poikiloderma and abbreviated as RTS. It is defined as a skin disease characterized by poikiloderma, congenital bone defects, and an increased risk of osteosarcoma in childhood and skin cancer later in life. The material basis for this condition is found in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DNA helicase gene RECQL4 on chromosome 8q24. ,Skin atrophy is a type of skin disease that is exactly synonymous with Atrophoderma, Atrophy - skin, and atrophic condition of skin.",4,True

""acroosteolysis with osteoporosis and changes in skull and mandible""@en,

,Hajdu Cheney Syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant and bone disease that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. :has_definition ""A connective tissue disease that is characterized by the accumulation of deposits of calcium and other minerals in elastic fibers, which are a component of connective tissue, this can result in changes in the skin, eyes, cardiovascular system and gastrointestinal system.""

,Pseudoxanthoma elasticum is a type of disease that falls under both autosomal recessive and connective tissue disease categories, and it specifically has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. :has_definition ""A bilirubin metabolic disorder that involves elevated levels of unconjugated bilirubin as bilirubin is not being conjugated as a result of reduced glucuronyltransferase activity.""

,Gilbert syndrome is a type of bilirubin metabolic disorder characterized by elevated levels of unconjugated bilirubin due to reduced glucuronyltransferase activity. It is precisely defined as a bilirubin metabolic disorder that involves these elevated levels because bilirubin is not being conjugated. Additionally, Gilbert syndrome is known by several exact synonyms, including Constitutional hyperbilirubinemia, Gilbert's disease, Gilbert's syndrome, Gilbert-Meulengracht syndrome, and hereditary nonhemolytic jaundice.",7,True
:has_definition ""An inherited metabolic disorder that involves elevated levels of bilirubin resulting from disruption of bilirubin metabolism.""

,Bilirubin metabolic disorder is a type of inherited metabolic disorder defined as an inherited metabolic disorder that involves elevated levels of bilirubin resulting from the disruption of bilirubin metabolism. It has the exact synonyms hereditary hyperbilirubinemia and hyperbilirubinemia, and it is also relatedly referred to as hyperbilirubinaemia.",5,True
:has_definition ""A sensory system disease that is characterized by auditory dysfunction located_in the auditory system.""

,An auditory system disease is the same as something that intersects with a disease located in the auditory system, which also encompasses any disease that at least has its location in the auditory system. It is a specific type of sensory system disease. Furthermore, an auditory system disease is defined as a sensory system disease characterized by auditory dysfunction located in the auditory system. In addition, it has the exact synonym ""ear and mastoid disease.""",4,True

:has_definition ""A glycogen storage disease that is characterized by onset of exercise intolerance and muscle cramps in childhood or adolescence and that has_material_basis_in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PYGM gene, which encodes muscle glycogen phosphorylase, on chromosome 11q13.""

,Glycogen storage disease V, also known exactly as Glycogen storage disease 5, Glycogen storage disease, type V, McArdle's disease, glycogen storage disease type V, and myophosphorylase deficiency, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and glycogen storage disease. It is characterized by a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined by the onset of exercise intolerance and muscle cramps in childhood or adolescence and has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PYGM gene, which encodes muscle glycogen phosphorylase, located on chromosome 11q13.",9,True

:has_definition ""A glycogen metabolism disorder that has_material_basis_in enzymes deficiencies necessary in the processing of glycogen synthesis or breakdown within muscles, liver, and other cell types.""

,Glycogen storage disease is a type of glycogen metabolism disorder characterized by enzyme deficiencies necessary for the processing of glycogen synthesis or breakdown within muscles, liver, and other cell types. It is also referred to as glycogenosis and, more specifically, as glycogenoses.",4,True

:has_definition ""A glycogen storage disease that is characterized by an accumulation of abnormal glycogen with short outer chains and that has_material_basis_in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the AGL gene, which encodes the glycogen debrancher enzyme, on chromosome 1p21.""

,Glycogen Storage Disease III is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of glycogen storage disease. It is characterized by an accumulation of abnormal glycogen with short outer chains, a condition that arises due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the AGL gene, encoding the glycogen debrancher enzyme, located on chromosome 1p21. This disease is also known by several exact synonyms including Glycogen Storage Disease 3, Glycogen Storage Disease, Type III, amylo 1,6 glucosidase deficiency, deficiency of debranching enzyme, and deficiency of dextrin.",9,True

:has_definition ""A glycogen storage disease I that has_material_basis_in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the G6PC gene, which encodes glucose-6-phosphatase (G6Pase), on chromosome 17q21."" .

,Glycogen storage disease Ia (GSD Ia) is recognized as a subtype of both glycogen storage disease I and autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and presents symptoms including hepatomegaly. Furthermore, GSD Ia is defined by having a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the G6PC gene, which is responsible for encoding glucose-6-phosphatase (G6Pase), located on chromosome 17q21.",5,True

,Gastric hemangioma is a type of gastrointestinal system benign neoplasm, a type of hemangioma, and a type of stomach disease. It is also classified as a type of condition that originates from endothelial cells and is located in the stomach. Additionally, gastric hemangioma is exactly synonymous with hemangioma of the stomach.",6,True

:has_definition ""A glycogen storage disease that has_material_basis_in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GBE1 gene, which encodes the glycogen branching enzyme, on chromosome 3p12.""

,Glycogen Storage Disease IV (GSD IV) is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of glycogen storage diseases. It specifically arises from either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GBE1 gene, which is responsible for encoding the glycogen branching enzyme, located on chromosome 3p12. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms including Amylopectinosis, Branching-transferase deficiency glycogenosis, Glycogen storage disease 4, Glycogen storage disease, type IV, brancher deficiency glycogenosis, and deficiency of 1,4-alpha-glucan branching enzyme.",10,True

:has_definition ""A glycogen storage disease that is characterized hepatomegaly, increased liver glycogen, and decreased leukocyte phosphorylase and results from the lack of expression of phosphorylase-b-kinase activity.""

,Glycogen storage disease VIII is a type of glycogen storage disease that is also categorized as an X-linked recessive disease, indicating it is a condition that has its material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. This disease is characterized by hepatomegaly, increased liver glycogen, and decreased leukocyte phosphorylase, resulting from the lack of expression of phosphorylase-b-kinase activity. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including Glycogen storage disease 8, Glycogen storage disease type VIII, Glycogenosis type VIII, and Hepatic glycogen phosphorylase kinase deficiency.",8,True

:has_definition ""A glycogen storage disease that has_material_basis_in deficiency of the lysosomal acid alpha-glucosidase enzyme resulting in damage to muscle and nerve cells due to an accumulation of glycogen in the lysosome.""

,Glycogen Storage Disease II (GSD II) is a type of Glycogen Storage Disease, which is also an Autosomal Recessive Disease. It is characterized by a deficiency of the lysosomal acid alpha-glucosidase enzyme, leading to damage to muscle and nerve cells due to an accumulation of glycogen in the lysosome. This condition is known by several exact synonyms, including Generalized Glycogenosis, Glycogen Storage Disease 2, Glycogen Storage Disease, Type II, Glycogenosis, Type 2, Lysosomal Alpha-1,4-Glucosidase Deficiency, Pompe's Disease, Acid Maltase Deficiency, Deficiency of Glucoamylase, Deficiency of Maltase, and Glycogen Storage Disease Type II.",14,True

:has_definition ""A glycogen storage disease characterized by enlargement of the liver, moderately low blood sugar, elevated levels of acetone and other ketone bodies in the blood and moderate growth retardation.""

,Glycogen storage disease VI is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of glycogen storage disease that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by an enlargement of the liver, moderately low blood sugar, elevated levels of acetone and other ketone bodies in the blood, and moderate growth retardation. Glycogen storage disease VI is also known by several exact synonyms including Glycogen storage disease 6, Hers' disease, glycogen storage disease type VI, hepatic glycogen phosphorylase deficiency, and hepatophosphorylase deficiency glycogenosis.",9,True

:has_definition ""A primary bacterial infectious disease that results_in infection, has_material_basis_in Mycobacterium avium complex (MAC), which is transmitted_by inhalation or transmitted_by ingestion of via the respiratory or gastrointestinal tract respectively. The bacteria cause disseminated infection in HIV infected people, while pulmonary disease in immunocompetent persons.""

,Mycobacterium avium complex disease is a type of primary bacterial infectious disease that has a material basis in Mycobacterium avium complex (MAC). This disease is transmitted by bacteria and specifically through airborne transmission. It results in infection and can be transmitted by inhalation or ingestion via the respiratory or gastrointestinal tract, respectively. This condition causes disseminated infection in HIV-infected individuals and pulmonary disease in immunocompetent persons. Mycobacterium avium complex disease is also known by exact synonyms such as Infection due to Mycobacterium intracellulare, MAC disease, Mycobacterium Avium Infection, and Mycobacterium avium Complex. Additionally, it has an exact match in the Medical Subject Headings (MESH) with the identifier D015270.",10,True

:has_definition ""An ethmoid sinus cancer that derives from epithelial cells of glandular origin.""

It has the exact synonym ""adenocarcinoma of the ethmoid sinus"" and a related synonym ""adenocarcinoma of ethmoid sinus.""",7,True

:has_definition ""A parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease that involves infection of the small intestine of humans, dogs and cats by the nematode Necator americanus causing abdominal pain, diarrhea, cramps, weight loss and anemia. Cutaneous larvae migrans in humans is characterized by skin ruptures and severe itching."" .

,Necatoriasis is a type of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease, which is defined as an infection of the small intestine in humans, dogs, and cats by the nematode Necator americanus. This disease results in symptoms such as abdominal pain, diarrhea, cramps, weight loss, and anemia, and is characterized by cutaneous larvae migrans in humans, leading to skin ruptures and severe itching. :has_definition ""A pneumonia located_in the lung parenchyma of unknown cause.""

,Idiopathic interstitial pneumonia is a type of pneumonia, which is a subset of diseases that feature some form of pneumonia. It is defined as a pneumonia located in the lung parenchyma of unknown cause. It also has exact synonyms, including Diffuse idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis and Idiopathic fibrosing alveolitis, and is relatedly referred to as IPF.",6,True

,Bronchiolitis obliterans is a type of bronchial disease and interstitial lung disease. It is characterized as an obstructive lung disease that involves the obstruction of the bronchioles due to inflammation and fibrosis, which occurs as a complication of various lung conditions or physiological insults. This disease is located in the bronchus and bronchiole. Bronchiolitis obliterans is also known by its exact synonyms: Bronchiolitis exudativa, Bronchiolitis fibrosa obliterans, and Obliterative bronchiolitis.",8,True
:has_definition ""A disease of anatomical entity that is located_in endocrine glands which secretes a type of hormone directly into the bloodstream to regulate the body."" .

,Endocrine system disease is equivalent to a condition that is both a disease and has a location within the endocrine system, where at least one disease affects the endocrine system. It is categorized as a type of disease of anatomical entities. Furthermore, an endocrine system disease is defined as a disease of anatomical entities situated in endocrine glands, which secrete hormones directly into the bloodstream to regulate the body.",3,True

:has_definition ""A idiopathic interstitial pneumonia which develops suddenly and is severe. Initially, the lung shows edema, hyaline membranes, and interstitial acute inflammation. Later, it develops loose organizing fibrosis, mostly within alveolar septa and type II pneumocyte hyperplasia. Fever, cough, and difficulty breathing develop over 1 to 2 weeks, typically progressing to acute respiratory failure.""

,Acute interstitial pneumonia (AIP) is a type of idiopathic interstitial pneumonia that is also known by several exact synonyms: Hamman-Rich disease, Hamman-Rich syndrome, the acute fatal form of idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis, accelerated interstitial pneumonia, and acute interstitial pneumonitis. This condition is characterized by sudden and severe development, with initial symptoms including fever, cough, and difficulty breathing that develop over 1 to 2 weeks, typically progressing to acute respiratory failure. Initially, the lung shows edema, hyaline membranes, and acute interstitial inflammation. Later stages involve the development of loose organizing fibrosis, mostly within alveolar septa, and type II pneumocyte hyperplasia. Additionally, acute interstitial pneumonia is a type of condition that at least has the symptom of some cough.",9,True

:has_definition ""An idiopathic interstitial pneumonia that occurs mainly in women, people who do not smoke, and people younger than 50 years with no known cause or risk factors. Lung biopsies may show predominantly interstitial inflammation or fibrosis or a combination of inflammation and fibrosis. A dry cough and shortness of breath develop over 6 to 18 months. Low-grade fever and a feeling of illness (malaise) may occur.""

,Nonspecific interstitial pneumonia (NSIP) is a type of idiopathic interstitial pneumonia, which is also recognized by its exact synonym, NSIP. It is characterized by having symptoms that include, at a minimum, a dry cough. NSIP is defined as an idiopathic interstitial pneumonia that primarily affects women, nonsmokers, and individuals younger than 50 years, with no known cause or risk factors identified. The condition manifests through lung biopsies that may reveal predominantly interstitial inflammation or fibrosis, or a combination of both inflammation and fibrosis. The development of a dry cough and shortness of breath occurs over a period of 6 to 18 months, and patients may also experience a low-grade fever and a general feeling of illness (malaise).",4,True

:has_definition ""A lung disease that is defined as a recurrent or chronic collapse of the right middle lobe, right upper lobe or lingula of the lung. It is caused by endobronchial tumour, granulomatous infections, lymphadenopathy, foreign bodies, endobronchial silicotic nodules, inspissated mucus associated with cystic fibrosis or inflammation as a result of an infection.""

,Middle Lobe Syndrome is a specific type of lung disease characterized by several symptoms, including some enlargement of lymph nodes, granulomatous inflammation, and lymphadenopathy. It is defined as a lung disease marked by the recurrent or chronic collapse of the right middle lobe, right upper lobe, or lingula of the lung. This condition can be caused by various factors such as endobronchial tumor, granulomatous infections, lymphadenopathy, foreign bodies, endobronchial silicotic nodules, inspissated mucus associated with cystic fibrosis, or inflammation due to an infection. Additionally, Middle Lobe Syndrome is precisely matched with the Medical Subject Headings (MESH) identifier D008878.",6,True

:has_definition ""A viral infectious disease that results_in infection in birds and humans, has_material_basis_in Avian orthoavulavirus 1, which is transmitted_by contact with feces and urine of an infected bird, or transmitted_by fomites. The infection has_symptom conjunctivitis, has_symptom headache, and has_symptom lacrimation in humans, and has_symptom gasping, has_symptom coughing, has_symptom twisting of head and neck, has_symptom circling, has_symptom complete paralysis, has_symptom watery diarrhea, and has_symptom reduced egg production in birds.""

,Newcastle disease is a viral infectious disease that is a type of ailment with a material basis in Avian orthoavulavirus 1. It can be transmitted by contact transmission and vehicle-borne fomite transmission. The disease exhibits symptoms such as paralysis, conjunctivitis, headache, diarrhea, and cough. Specifically, Newcastle disease is defined as a viral infectious condition resulting in infection in birds and humans, caused by Avian orthoavulavirus 1. This disease is spread through contact with feces and urine of an infected bird or by fomites. In humans, the infection presents symptoms like conjunctivitis, headache, and lacrimation, while in birds, it manifests as gasping, coughing, twisting of the head and neck, circling, complete paralysis, watery diarrhea, and reduced egg production. Additionally, Newcastle disease is also known by the exact synonyms Newcastle's disease and Pseudo-fowlpest.",11,True

,Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD) is a type of obstructive lung disease with a definition that describes it as a chronic and progressive disorder of small airways in the lungs. ,Tropical spastic paraparesis is a type of spinal cord disease, which is also a viral infectious disease. It has a material basis in the Human T-cell leukemia virus type I and is transmitted through contact transmission and vehicle borne ingestion transmission. The disease manifests with symptoms such as muscle weakness and sensory disturbance, and it primarily affects the spinal cord. Tropical spastic paraparesis is defined as a viral infectious disease resulting in inflammation located in the spinal cord, caused by Human T-lymphotropic virus 1. It is transmitted by sexual contact and breast feeding, leading to symptoms such as spastic weakness of both legs, muscle stiffness, sensory disturbance, and spasms. Additionally, tropical spastic paraparesis is synonymously known as HTLV-associated myelopathy, Tropical spastic paralysis, and Tropical spastic paraplegia.",11,True

Furthermore, Pelizaeus-Merzbacher disease is known by several exact synonyms, including HLD1, Leukodystrophy, sudanophilic, PMD, Pelizaeus Merzbacher brain sclerosis (also spelled as Pelizaeus-Merzbacher brain sclerosis), diffuse familial brain sclerosis, hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 1, and sudanophilic leukodystrophy, Pelizaeus-Merzbacher type.",12,True

:has_definition ""A pneumonia that is defined as an acute lung injury after the inhalation of foreign material such as regurgitated acidic gastric contents, petroleum products and laxative oils. This syndrome occurs in patients who have a marked disturbance of consciousness such as that resulting from a drug overdose, seizures, a massive cerebrovascular accident, or the use of anesthesia. Aspiration of gastric contents results in a chemical burn of the tracheobronchial tree and pulmonary parenchyma, causing an intense parenchymal inflammatory reaction. The disease has_symptom non-productive cough, has_symptom tachypnea, has_symptom bronchospasm, has_symptom bloody sputum, has_symptom frothy sputum, or has_symptom respiratory distress, 2-5 hrs after aspiration.""

,Aspiration pneumonitis is a type of pneumonia characterized by several symptoms, including bloody sputum, tachypnea, cough, bronchospasm, and cerebrovascular accident. It is also defined as an acute lung injury following the inhalation of foreign materials such as regurgitated acidic gastric contents, petroleum products, and laxative oils. This condition often occurs in patients who experience a significant disturbance of consciousness due to factors like drug overdose, seizures, a massive cerebrovascular accident, or the use of anesthesia. The inhalation of gastric contents leads to a chemical burn of the tracheobronchial tree and pulmonary parenchyma, which results in an intense inflammatory reaction within the lung tissue. The disease manifests symptoms such as a non-productive cough, tachypnea, bronchospasm, bloody sputum, frothy sputum, or respiratory distress, typically 2-5 hours after aspiration. Additionally, aspiration pneumonitis is known by exact synonyms such as Chemical pneumonitis and Mendelson's Syndrome, and it features pneumonia as a significant aspect of its pathology.",10,True

:has_definition ""An aspiration pneumonitis resulting from the aspiration of lipids. It is the result of a foreign body-type reaction to the presence of lipid material within the lung parenchyma. It is caused by inhalation of nasal drops with oil base or cosmetic oil and aspiration of mineral oil when used as a laxative agent.""

,Lipid pneumonia is a type of aspiration pneumonitis, defined as an aspiration pneumonitis resulting from the aspiration of lipids. It occurs due to a foreign body-type reaction to the presence of lipid material within the lung parenchyma, caused by the inhalation of nasal drops with an oil base or cosmetic oil, and the aspiration of mineral oil when used as a laxative agent. Lipid pneumonia is also exactly synonymous with Exogenous lipoid pneumonia and Lipoid pneumonitis.",4,True

column2: it occurs most often in the head and neck area or in the genital or urinary organs."" .

:has_definition ""A thymus cancer that derives_from epithelial cells. The tumor cells in a thymic carcinoma look very different from the normal cells of the thymus, grow more quickly, and have usually spread to other parts of the body when the cancer is found.""

,Thymic carcinoma is a type of carcinoma, also referred to as thymus cancer, and is characterized by a derivation from epithelial cells. It is defined as a thymus cancer that originates from epithelial cells, with tumor cells that appear significantly different from the normal thymus cells, exhibiting rapid growth and typically having spread to other body parts at the time of diagnosis. Additionally, thymic carcinoma is precisely synonymous with malignant Thymoma, indicating an exact correspondence in terms of its medical identification.",6,True

:has_definition ""A viral infectious disease that results in infection of primates, rodents and humans, located in skin, has_material_basis_in Monkeypox virus, which is transmitted by contact with the animal's blood, body fluids, rash, or with the body fluids of a sick person, transmitted by fomites, and transmitted by respiratory droplets. The infection has symptom fever, has symptom muscle ache, has symptom headache, and has symptom lymphadenopathy.""

,Mpox, also known as monkeypox, is a type of viral infectious disease that results in the infection of primates, rodents, and humans. It is primarily located in the skin and has its material basis in the Monkeypox virus. This disease can be transmitted in several ways, including contact with an infected animal's blood, body fluids, rash, or with the body fluids of a sick person. Additionally, it can be transmitted through fomites and respiratory droplets. The means of transmission encompass a union of contact transmission, droplet spread transmission, and vehicle-borne fomite transmission. Common symptoms of mpox include fever, headache, muscle ache, and lymphadenopathy.",6,True

:has_definition ""A viral infectious disease that results_in infection, located_in skin, has_material_basis_in Vaccinia virus, which is used as a live vaccine against smallpox. The virus is transmitted_by contact with the vaccination site before it has healed, or transmitted_by fomites that have been contaminated with live virus from the vaccination site. The infection has_symptom rash, has_symptom fever, and has_symptom body aches."" .

,Vaccinia is a viral infectious disease with a material basis in the Vaccinia virus, which is utilized as a live vaccine against smallpox. This disease is characterized by symptoms such as body aches, rash, and fever. It primarily affects the skin and is transmitted either through contact with the vaccination site before it has healed or via fomites contaminated with live virus from the vaccination site, involving both contact and vehicle-borne fomite transmission.",7,True

,Gonadoblastoma is a type of cell type benign neoplasm, which is defined as a cell type benign neoplasm composed of a mixture of gonadal elements, such as large primordial germ cells, immature Sertoli cells or granulosa cells of the sex cord, and gonadal stromal cells, including granulosa, theca, and fibrocyte cells. :has_definition ""A GM2 gangliosidosis that is characterized onset in infancy of developmental retardation, followed by paralysis, dementia and blindness, with death in the second or third year of life and has_material_basis_in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the alpha subunit of the hexosaminidase A gene (HEXA) on chromosome 15q23.""@en

,Tay-Sachs disease, also precisely known as GM2 gangliosidosis, type 1 or hexosaminidase A deficiency, is a specific form of GM2 gangliosidosis. It typically emerges during childhood and is defined by its onset in infancy, marked by developmental retardation, followed by paralysis, dementia, and blindness, leading to death in the second or third year of life. The disease's material basis is found in either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the alpha subunit of the hexosaminidase A gene (HEXA) located on chromosome 15q23.",5,True

It is also exactly synonymous with Beta-galactosidase deficiency, deficiency of beta-galactosidase, and gangliosidosis GM1.",5,True
